@feat-eval-gc
Feature: General-Capability Regression Suite for Fine-Tune Gating
  As the fine-tune deploy gatekeeper (D-OBS-3, paired-grade rule S10 §2.5)
  I want a frozen HumanEval/MBPP slice runnable against served GGUFs
  So that catastrophic forgetting is measured on every fine-tune grade instead of assumed away

  Background:
    Given the frozen suites (po, arch, coach, qav) are green and their tasks, thresholds, and graders are unedited
    And the gc-heldout suite is installed additively as tasks gc-held-001-humaneval and gc-held-002-mbpp

  # ── GROUP A: Key Examples ──────────────────────────────────────────────

  # Why: A task whose Oracle fails is a broken verifier, not a hard task (§3.5 house rule)
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=medium] The fixed subset is committed in-repo with per-row SHA-256 pins and licence/provenance record (HumanEval MIT, MBPP CC BY 4.0); the private-asset symlink farm is not deepened
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: The canonical benchmark solutions pass every row
    Given each pinned row's canonical solution installed as the task Oracle
    When the gate battery runs against the Oracle solutions in the execution sandbox
    Then every row should grade PASS on both tasks

  # Why: The core happy path — the suite exists to grade served checkpoints, not local weights
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=medium] The runner is a direct-serving stand-in per the run_coach_heldout.py precedent, not run_po_eval.py
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=high] K = 3 reps per task, the house convention across all four frozen suites
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=medium] Sampling is serving-faithful — the candidate seat's deployed posture where one exists; base baselines at temp 0.1 / top_p 0.9
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=medium] Each row's prompt wraps the benchmark content in a pinned minimal instruction, hash-recorded per rep; MBPP rows include the benchmark's reference asserts per the standard convention
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: A served checkpoint is graded end to end with per-rep records
    Given a checkpoint served via llama-swap under its serving handle
    When the gc-heldout runner executes both tasks for K reps
    Then each rep should produce a config record pinning model id, lineage, quant, template, sampling, and prompt hashes
    And each rep should produce a per-row grade and a pass-at-1 count per benchmark

  # Why: The gate's PASS direction — paired against the frozen base baseline, never absolute
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=low] No absolute floor in v1 — the gate is purely baseline-relative; a floor may be added additively at freeze once the base baseline is measured
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: A candidate within the frozen regression margin passes the gate
    Given a frozen base-model baseline for the candidate's base and quant family
    And a candidate whose per-rep solved count is within the frozen margin of that baseline on both benchmarks
    When the pre-registered verdict is applied
    Then the general-capability side should read PASS

  # Why: The reason the suite exists — forgetting caught mechanically before deploy
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=medium] Gates are G-G1 validity/extraction, G-G2 HumanEval floor, G-G3 MBPP floor, G-G4 sandbox+pin integrity (standing pre-grade); G-G2/G-G3 FAIL routes NO-DEPLOY, G-G1 routes serving/harness defect, G-G4 blocks grading not the candidate
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: A candidate that regresses beyond the margin is dispositioned NO-DEPLOY
    Given a candidate whose solved count falls below the frozen margin on any rep of either benchmark
    When the pre-registered verdict is applied
    Then the disposition should be NO-DEPLOY with the failing benchmark and lost rows named in the RESULTS record

  # Why: S10 §2.5 paired-grade rule binds from first availability
  @key-example
  Scenario: Every fine-tune grade pairs the role suite with the general-capability slice
    Given a fine-tune candidate graded against its frozen role suite
    When the grade run is recorded
    Then the RESULTS record should carry both the role-suite verdict and the general-capability verdict for the same candidate and serving config

  # Why: Additive-only house rule — the frozen suites must be provably untouched
  @key-example @smoke @regression
  Scenario: Installing the suite leaves every frozen suite byte-identical
    Given the pre-existing integrity battery's node list and verdicts captured before installation
    When the full test battery runs with the gc-heldout suite present
    Then every pre-existing node should pass with an identical verdict
    And the frozen suites' task globs should remain blind to gc-held tasks by construction

  # Why: The sandbox is the load-bearing new mechanism — verdicts come from executed assertions
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=medium] Sandbox = stdlib-only subprocess, no Docker: fresh isolated interpreter per row, scrubbed environment, throwaway scratch CWD, resource limits, network denied via an unshared network namespace where the host permits
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: Candidate code is graded by execution inside the sandbox
    Given an extracted candidate program for a pinned row
    When the row is graded
    Then the program should run in a fresh isolated interpreter in a throwaway scratch directory
    And the row verdict should come from the executed reference assertions, never from text matching

  # ── GROUP B: Boundary Conditions ───────────────────────────────────────

  # Why: Just-inside/at the frozen margin — the gate must not be stricter than registered
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=low] Margin is an integer row count per benchmark per rep: candidate solved count >= baseline - 2 rows, required 3/3 reps
  @boundary
  Scenario Outline: Solved counts at or inside the margin pass
    Given a frozen baseline of <baseline> solved rows on a benchmark
    And a candidate rep solving <candidate> rows
    When the regression floor is applied
    Then the rep should <result> on that benchmark

    Examples:
      | baseline | candidate | result |
      | 20       | 20        | pass   |
      | 20       | 18        | pass   |
      | 20       | 17        | fail   |

  # Why: Per-row execution timeout is a grading boundary, not a run abort
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=medium] Per-row execution timeout is 10 seconds wall-clock; generation timeout is 300 seconds per model call
  @boundary
  Scenario: A row finishing just inside the execution timeout grades on merit
    Given a candidate program that completes just under the per-row timeout
    When the row is graded
    Then the verdict should come from its executed assertions

  # Why: Just-outside pair — at/over the timeout the row fails but the run continues
  @boundary @negative
  Scenario: A row exceeding the execution timeout is failed and the run continues
    Given a candidate program still running at the per-row timeout
    When the sandbox kills it
    Then the row should grade FAIL with a timeout reason
    And the remaining rows and reps should grade normally

  # Why: Content pinning — one drifted byte in a frozen row invalidates grading
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=low] The fixed subset is 25 HumanEval + 25 MBPP rows, selected by ascending benchmark task-id after excluding rows whose canonical solution fails under the pinned interpreter, each content-pinned by SHA-256
  @boundary @negative @smoke
  Scenario: A drifted pinned row blocks grading
    Given a pinned benchmark row whose content no longer matches its recorded hash
    When the pre-grade integrity gate runs
    Then grading should be blocked before any model is called
    And the drifted row should be named

  # Why: Validity-gate convention — incomplete is INVALID, never a silent FAIL or skip
  @boundary
  Scenario: A run missing a rep is INVALID rather than failed
    Given a grade run where one rep aborted before producing its records
    When the run is assessed against the validity gate
    Then the run should be INVALID with the missing rep named
    And the missing rep should be re-run in place rather than skipped

  # Why: Extraction faithful to the serving parse posture — trailing echo tolerated, per the runtime cascade
  @boundary
  Scenario: A response with one code fence followed by trailing prose still grades
    Given a model response containing exactly one fenced code block followed by explanatory text
    When the candidate program is extracted under the pinned extraction contract
    Then the fenced program should be the graded candidate

  # ── GROUP C: Negative Cases ────────────────────────────────────────────

  # Why: Unparseable output is a row FAIL under the contract, not a harness crash or an INVALID run
  @negative
  Scenario: A prose-only response with no extractable code fails the row cleanly
    Given a model response containing no extractable program
    When the row is graded
    Then the row should grade FAIL with an extraction reason
    And the harness should proceed to the next row

  # Why: Broken code and wrong code are distinct failure surfaces; both must fail by execution
  @negative
  Scenario Outline: Defective candidate programs fail their rows by execution
    Given a candidate program that <defect>
    When the row is graded in the sandbox
    Then the row should grade FAIL with an execution reason

    Examples:
      | defect                                        |
      | raises an error before defining the function  |
      | returns wrong answers for the reference cases |
      | defines the wrong function name               |

  # Why: The no-network constraint is enforced on generated code, not just the graders
  @negative @smoke
  Scenario: A candidate program that attempts network access is denied and fails
    Given a candidate program that attempts an outbound connection
    When the row is graded in the sandbox
    Then the connection attempt should be denied inside the sandbox
    And the row should grade FAIL
    And the grader itself should complete without any network access

  # Why: Runaway code must not take the host or the run down
  @negative @edge-case
  Scenario: An infinite loop is killed at the timeout without harming the run
    Given a candidate program that loops forever
    When the row is graded
    Then the sandbox should kill it at the per-row timeout
    And the host and the remaining rows should be unaffected

  # Why: Generated code must not be able to touch the repository or other rows' state
  @negative @smoke
  Scenario: A candidate program writing outside its scratch directory leaves the repo untouched
    Given a candidate program that writes files outside its working directory
    When the row is graded and the run completes
    Then the repository working tree should be unchanged
    And no other row's scratch state should be affected

  # Why: The paired comparison is meaningless against a drifted or absent baseline
  @negative
  Scenario: Grading is blocked when the frozen baseline record is missing or drifted
    Given a candidate whose base and quant family has no intact frozen baseline record
    When a grade run is requested
    Then grading should be blocked with the baseline gap named
    And the disposition should route to measuring a baseline additively, not to skipping the general side

  # Why: Suite output isolation — the qav §5 rule generalized
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=high] Suite is gc-heldout, tasks gc-held-001-humaneval / gc-held-002-mbpp, runs under runs/gc-heldout/<candidate>-<date>/
  @negative
  Scenario: A gc-heldout run refuses to reuse another suite's output directory
    Given an output directory already holding another suite's run records
    When a gc-heldout run is started against it
    Then the run should refuse to start

  # Why: Row identity must be unambiguous across the two benchmark subsets
  @negative
  Scenario: Row-id collisions across the benchmark subsets are forbidden
    Given the pinned manifests for both benchmark subsets
    When the manifest integrity test runs
    Then every row id should be unique across the whole suite

  # Why: A truncated generation is a distinct diagnosable failure, not wrong code
  @negative @edge-case
  Scenario: A truncated response fails the row with the truncation recorded
    Given a model response whose generation was cut at the length limit
    When the row is graded
    Then the row should grade FAIL
    And the truncation reason should be recorded as a diagnostic distinguishable from an execution failure

  # ── GROUP D: Edge Cases ────────────────────────────────────────────────

  # Why: The sandbox decision is refuse-loud, never degrade — grading unsandboxed silently would be worse than not grading
  @edge-case @smoke
  Scenario: An unavailable sandbox blocks grading rather than degrading
    Given a host where the sandbox isolation mechanism cannot be established
    When a grade run is requested
    Then the run should refuse to start with the missing isolation named
    And no candidate code should execute unsandboxed

  # Why: Resource exhaustion is the accident class the sandbox exists for
  @edge-case
  Scenario: A memory-hungry candidate is contained by the sandbox limits
    Given a candidate program that allocates memory without bound
    When the row is graded
    Then the sandbox resource limits should terminate it
    And the row should grade FAIL while the host stays stable

  # Why: The quant lesson from the first graded run — coach-ft-v3 Q4_K_M vs base Q4_K_XL; cross-quant deltas absorb the margin
  @edge-case @regression
  Scenario: A candidate is only compared against a baseline of its own base and quant family
    Given frozen baselines recorded per base model and quant family
    And a candidate whose lineage differs in quant from an existing baseline
    When the paired comparison is selected
    Then the comparison should require a matching-family baseline
    And a new family's baseline should be added additively before that family's first grade

  # Why: The GB10 serving reality — swaps and evictions mid-run happened in the first graded run
  @edge-case
  Scenario: A rep aborted by a serving eviction is re-run in place
    Given a rep aborted because the served model was evicted mid-run
    When the run is completed
    Then the aborted rep should be re-run in place under the same pinned config
    And the RESULTS record should list the abort and the re-run evidence

  # Why: Benchmark data quality — a canonical solution that fails locally poisons the Oracle gate
  @edge-case
  Scenario: A benchmark row whose canonical solution fails locally is excluded at build time
    Given a candidate benchmark row whose canonical solution fails under the pinned interpreter
    When the fixed subset is selected
    Then the row should be excluded before pinning
    And the exclusion should be recorded in the subset's provenance

  # Why: Contamination honesty — pre-register what the suite can and cannot claim
  @edge-case
  Scenario: The suite reports relative regression and never absolute capability
    Given the pinned benchmarks are public data present in base-model pretraining
    When any RESULTS record is written
    Then the verdict should be expressed as regression against the frozen base baseline
    And the contamination residual should be carried in the record by construction

  # Why: Host secrets must be invisible to generated code — the sandbox env is scrubbed
  @edge-case
  Scenario: A candidate program reading environment variables sees no host secrets
    Given a candidate program that enumerates its environment
    When the row is graded in the sandbox
    Then no host credential or token should be visible to the program

  # Why: Fork-bomb class is distinct from the memory class — process count is limited
  @edge-case
  Scenario: A candidate program spawning child processes is contained
    Given a candidate program that spawns child processes without bound
    When the row is graded
    Then the sandbox process limit should contain it
    And the row should grade FAIL while the host stays stable

  # Why: A grader bug must never masquerade as a candidate failure — it routes to the harness-defect gate
  @edge-case
  Scenario: A grader crash is recorded as a harness defect rather than a candidate failure
    Given a row where the grader itself crashes
    When the run is assessed
    Then the crash should be recorded as a harness defect against the validity gate
    And the row should not be recorded as a candidate FAIL

  # Why: Transport failure produces an aborted rep, never a fabricated grade
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=high] Transport retries are 2 per rep, then abort-and-report — the RETRIES_PER_REP precedent
  @edge-case
  Scenario: An unreachable serving endpoint aborts the rep after pinned retries
    Given the llama-swap endpoint is unreachable
    When a rep is executed
    Then the runner should retry the pinned number of times
    And the rep should abort with the transport failure reported
    And no fabricated or empty response should ever be graded
